  "tutor_notes": {
    "block1_script": "Hey Pirate! Today we're learning DIVISION — the superpower of sharing things fairly. Imagine you have 12 cookies and 3 friends. Division helps you give everyone the exact same amount. No one gets extra, no one gets less. That's what makes division so magical — it creates perfect fairness! Let's start by sharing some Blue Island treasures into equal groups.",
    "block2_hint": "When you see the ÷ symbol, think 'split into equal parts.' The number before ÷ is what you're sharing. The number after ÷ is how many groups you're making. Your answer is how many go in EACH group. Try saying it out loud: '12 divided by 3 equals 4' means 12 things split into 3 groups gives you 4 in each group.",
    "block3_tips": [
      "Draw circles for each group and put dots inside until you use all the items",
      "Use your fingers: if dividing by 3, hold up 3 fingers and count items onto each finger equally",
      "Think backwards from multiplication: 3 × 4 = 12, so 12 ÷ 3 = 4",
      "Practice with real objects at home: share toys, crackers, or blocks with family"
    ],
    "block5_abstraction": "Division is the opposite of multiplication. When we multiply 3 × 4, we combine groups to get 12 total. When we divide 12 ÷ 3, we break 12 apart into 3 equal groups of 4. Division answers the question: 'If I split this total into this many groups, how many are in each group?' It's like being a fair judge who makes sure everyone gets the exact same share — no arguments, no leftovers, perfectly balanced!",
    "weak_point_focus": "If you forget the answer, don't panic! Use the skip-counting trick: for 12 ÷ 3, count by 3s (3, 6, 9, 12) on your fingers. You counted 4 times, so the answer is 4! Or think: 'What number times 3 gives me 12?' Practice the small division facts (÷2, ÷3, ÷4) until they feel automatic, then bigger numbers will be easy."
  }
